CO2 methanation (CO2+4H2=CH4+2H2O(g),δH298K0=-164kJmol-1)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\rm{C}}{{\rm{O}}_{\rm{2}}}{\rm{ + 4}}{{\rm{H}}_{\rm{2}}}{\rm{ = C}}{{\rm{H}}_{\rm{4}}}{\rm{ + 2}}{{\rm{H}}_{\rm{2}}}{\rm{O(g),\;}} \delta {\rm{H}}_{{\rm{298K}}}^{\rm{0}}{\rm{ = }} - {\rm{164\;kJ\;mo}}{{\rm{l}}^{ - {\rm{1}}}})$$\end{document} is considered as an important application of the catalyst-loaded MEPCM because of its demand for high thermal control26. It presents an alternative to conventional natural gas production by converting CO2 to CH4, which is effective for reducing CO2 emissions27. Additionally, CH4 is superior to H2 in terms of capital expenditure as transportation of CH4 can be achieved by using existing natural gas pipelines27,28. Based on the above, a power-to-gas system employing CO2 methanation has been previously proposed25,29,30. CO2 methanation requires catalysts (Ni, Rh, Ru, etc.), and Ni, which is the most widely used, shows high catalytic activity from 300 to 400 °C28,31. However, thermal runaway is a concern due to the highly exothermic reaction32–34. The use of a Ni-loaded MEPCM (Ni/MEPCM) instead of a conventional catalyst may suppress a significant rise in temperature.

MEPCM was prepared from Al-Si microspheres (25 mass% Si; Diameter: < 38 μm\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
